Easiness-time-level plot.

This function computes a graph displaying the guessers plot for each quiz.

plot_etl(quiz_object, challengeLevel, item = "item",
  rating = "cognitive_level")

Arguments

challengeLevel

file of challengue level
df_quizzes

dataframe in long format of all quizzes (Generated with read_lc)

Value

The ETL plot

Examples

file_to_read <- "../../datasets/sample_dataset/Q01.csv"
file_cognitivelevel <- "../../datasets/sample_dataset/cognitive_file.csv"
quiz_object <- read_lc(file_to_read)
#> Parsed with column specification:
#> cols(
#>   .default = col_datetime(),
#>   `email address` = col_character(),
#>   `item01 score` = col_integer(),
#>   `item02 score` = col_integer(),
#>   `item03 score` = col_integer(),
#>   `item04 score` = col_integer(),
#>   `item05 score` = col_integer(),
#>   `item06 score` = col_integer(),
#>   `item07 score` = col_integer(),
#>   `item08 score` = col_integer(),
#>   `item09 score` = col_integer(),
#>   `item10 score` = col_integer(),
#>   `item11 score` = col_integer()
#> )
#> See spec(...) for full column specifications.
#> Joining, by = c("email address", "question")
cognitive_level <- data.frame(read_csv(file_cognitivelevel))
#> Parsed with column specification:
#> cols(
#>   item = col_character(),
#>   cognitive_level = col_integer()
#> )
quiz_object <- add_times(quiz_object)
plot_etl(quiz_object, cognitive_level)
#> Adding missing grouping variables: `quiz`
#> Joining, by = "question_id"
#> Joining, by = "rating"
